Data Exercise 2: Mice Jumping (Parker)

Vidushi Kataria

2024-10-23

Libraries

library(tidyverse)
files <- list.files(path = "jumping_data_parker/",
                         pattern = "*.csv",
                         full.names = TRUE)

files
convert_columns <- function(file) {
  file <- file %>%
    mutate(sex = case_when(sex == FALSE ~ "F",
                         sex == "M" ~ "M"),
           date = as.character(date))
}
raw_data <- map(files, read_csv) %>%
  map(convert_columns) %>%
  bind_rows()

inspect data

raw_data %>%
  distinct(sex)
raw_data %>%
  distinct(condition)
raw_data %>%
  distinct(laser_trial)

explore the data

summary_data <- raw_data %>%
  group_by(subject, distance) %>%
  summarise(succ_rate = sum(outcome == 1)/n())
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'subject'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
summary_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = succ_rate)) +
  geom_histogram()

plot the data

summary_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = distance,
             y = succ_rate,
             group = subject)) +
  geom_line() +
  ylim(0, 1)

raw_data %>%
  group_by(subject, distance) %>%
  mutate(succ_rate_NOabort = sum(outcome == 1)/(n() - sum(outcome == 2)))
raw_data %>%
  group_by(subject, distance) %>%
# filter(outcome == 1 | outcome == 0)
# filter(outcome != 2) 
  filter(outcome %in% c(0, 1)) %>%
  summarise(succ_rate = sum(outcome == 1)/n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = distance,
             y = succ_rate,
             group = subject)) +
  geom_line() +
  ylim(0, 1)
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'subject'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Day 2

3 goals today - Make our plot look (literally) like theirs in terms of the visual features - Explore a different feature of the dataset. What other questions might we ask, what plots will allow us to answer them? -

raw_data %>%
  group_by(subject, distance) %>%
# filter(outcome == 1 | outcome == 0)
# filter(outcome != 2) 
  filter(outcome %in% c(0, 1)) %>%
  summarise(succ_rate = sum(outcome == 1)/n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = distance,
             y = succ_rate)) +
  geom_line(aes(group = subject), alpha = 0.3, color = "darkblue") +
  stat_summary(fun.data = "mean_se", geom = "errorbar", width = 0.2, color = "darkblue") +
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "line", color = "darkblue") + 
  ylim(0, 1) +
  xlim(10, 25) +
  labs(x = "gap distance (cm)",
       y = "success rate") +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
        axis.line = element_line(color = "black", linewidth = 0.5)) +
  annotate(geom = "text", label = "binocular",
           x = 11, y = 0.1, color = "darkblue")

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'subject'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

explore something new

raw_data %>%
  filter(outcome %in% c(0,1)) %>%
  group_by(subject, experimenter) %>%
  summarise(succ_rate = sum(outcome == 1)/n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = succ_rate,
             x = experimenter)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3, width = 0.1, height = 0) +
  ylim(0, 1)
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'subject'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
